QUESTION_BANK[2].push(
{ q:"Superposition theorem is applicable to circuits that are:",
  opts:["Linear and bilateral, containing multiple independent sources","Non-linear only, with a single source","Purely resistive, with no sources at all","Only circuits with exactly two sources"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Superposition requires linearity and bilateral elements — the response is found by summing the effect of each independent source acting alone, with others zeroed." },
{ q:"Superposition theorem cannot be directly used to calculate:",
  opts:["Power, since it is a non-linear (quadratic) function of current or voltage","Voltage across any resistor","Current through any branch","Total resistance of a network"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Since power = I²R (quadratic), simply summing the power contributions from each source acting alone does not give the correct total power in the presence of multiple sources." },
{ q:"Thevenin's theorem states that any linear two-terminal network can be replaced by a single voltage source Vth in series with a resistance Rth, where Rth is found by:",
  opts:["Deactivating all independent sources and finding the resistance seen from the terminals","Measuring the short-circuit current at the terminals","Adding all source resistances directly","Dividing the open-circuit voltage by the short-circuit current only, without deactivating sources"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Rth is obtained by zeroing all independent sources (voltage sources shorted, current sources opened) and calculating the equivalent resistance looking into the terminals." },
{ q:"A Thevenin equivalent circuit has Vth = 20 V and Rth = 4 Ω. Find the equivalent Norton current source value.",
  opts:["5 A","4 A","80 A","0.2 A"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"IN = Vth/Rth = 20/4 = 5 A, with the Norton resistance equal to Rth = 4 Ω in parallel." },
{ q:"Millman's theorem is used to find:",
  opts:["The common voltage across several parallel branches, each with its own EMF and series resistance","The current through a single resistor only","The power dissipated in a purely resistive circuit","The resonant frequency of an RLC circuit"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Millman's theorem combines multiple voltage-source-with-resistance branches connected in parallel into a single equivalent voltage using V = Σ(E/R) / Σ(1/R)." },
{ q:"Two parallel branches feed a common node: Branch 1 has E1=10V, R1=2Ω; Branch 2 has E2=20V, R2=4Ω. Find the Millman voltage across the common node.",
  opts:["13.33 V","15 V","10 V","20 V"], ans:0, level:"Hard", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"V = (E1/R1 + E2/R2)/(1/R1 + 1/R2) = (10/2 + 20/4)/(1/2 + 1/4) = (5+5)/0.75 = 13.33 V." },
{ q:"The Reciprocity theorem states that in a linear, bilateral, single-source network, the ratio of response to excitation:",
  opts:["Remains unchanged even if the positions of the source and response (ammeter) are interchanged","Doubles when source and response positions are interchanged","Becomes zero when source and response positions are interchanged","Is undefined for any interchange of source and response"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Reciprocity guarantees the excitation-to-response ratio is preserved under interchange, valid only for linear, bilateral, single-source networks." },
{ q:"The Reciprocity theorem is applicable only to networks that have:",
  opts:["A single independent source","At least two independent sources","No sources at all","Only non-linear elements"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Reciprocity is defined and valid specifically for single-source, linear, bilateral networks." },
{ q:"Tellegen's theorem is fundamentally based on the principle of:",
  opts:["Conservation of power in any lumped network satisfying KCL and KVL","Conservation of resistance in a network","Maximum power transfer between source and load","Superposition of multiple independent sources"], ans:0, level:"Hard", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Tellegen's theorem states that the sum of power delivered equals the sum of power absorbed in any network obeying KCL and KVL — valid even for non-linear or time-varying networks." },
{ q:"The Compensation theorem states that if the resistance of a branch carrying current I is changed by ΔR, the resulting change in currents can be found by:",
  opts:["Inserting a voltage source of value I×ΔR in that branch, with all other sources zeroed","Doubling the current in every other branch","Removing that branch entirely from the circuit","Adding a current source of value I/ΔR in that branch"], ans:0, level:"Hard", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"The compensation theorem replaces the resistance change with an equivalent compensating voltage source (I×ΔR) to analyse the resulting current changes throughout the network." },
{ q:"The Substitution theorem states that any branch of a network can be replaced by an equivalent branch, provided the replacement:",
  opts:["Produces the same voltage and current as the original branch, with all other conditions unchanged","Has exactly double the resistance of the original branch","Removes all sources from the network","Is always a pure resistor, regardless of the original branch"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Substitution theorem is mainly used for verification — any branch can be swapped for another that maintains identical terminal voltage and current." },
{ q:"For maximum power transfer in an AC circuit with complex source impedance Zth, the condition on load impedance ZL is:",
  opts:["ZL equals the complex conjugate of Zth (ZL = Zth*)","ZL equals Zth exactly, including phase angle","ZL is purely resistive, regardless of Zth","ZL is as large as possible"], ans:0, level:"Hard", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Maximum power transfer in AC circuits with complex impedances requires conjugate matching, ZL = Zth*, so the reactive parts cancel and resistances match." },
{ q:"For maximum power transfer in a purely resistive DC network, the condition is:",
  opts:["RL = Rth (load resistance equals Thevenin/source resistance)","RL = 2×Rth","RL is as small as possible","RL = 0"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"In the purely resistive case, maximum power transfer simplifies to matching the load resistance directly to the source's Thevenin resistance." },
{ q:"'Duality' in electric circuit theory refers to:",
  opts:["A pair of relationships where series↔parallel, voltage↔current, and similar dual quantities are interchanged","Having exactly two independent sources in a network","A network that behaves identically under AC and DC","Two identical resistors connected in series"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Dual circuits/equations exhibit a systematic interchange of corresponding quantities (e.g., mesh↔node, series↔parallel, R↔G, L↔C)." },
{ q:"The dual of a series RLC circuit is:",
  opts:["A parallel RLC circuit, with R↔G, L↔C","Another series RLC circuit with doubled values","A purely resistive circuit","A circuit with no reactive elements at all"], ans:0, level:"Hard", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Applying duality to a series RLC circuit swaps series↔parallel topology and interchanges R with conductance G, and L with C." },
{ q:"An ideal voltage source has:",
  opts:["Zero internal resistance","Infinite internal resistance","Internal resistance exactly equal to the load resistance","Internal resistance that varies with current"], ans:0, level:"Easy", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"An ideal voltage source maintains its rated voltage regardless of current drawn, implying zero internal resistance." },
{ q:"An ideal current source has:",
  opts:["Infinite internal resistance","Zero internal resistance","Internal resistance exactly equal to the load resistance","Internal resistance that decreases with voltage"], ans:0, level:"Easy", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"An ideal current source maintains its rated current regardless of the voltage across it, implying infinite internal (parallel) resistance." },
{ q:"Source transformation converts a voltage source V with series resistance R into an equivalent current source of value:",
  opts:["I = V/R, with the same resistance R now placed in parallel","I = V×R, with R remaining in series","I = R/V, with R removed entirely","I = V, regardless of R"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Source transformation preserves terminal behaviour by converting a series voltage-resistance combination into an equivalent parallel current-resistance combination." },
{ q:"Convert a 24 V source with 6 Ω series resistance into its equivalent current source form. What is the equivalent current value?",
  opts:["4 A","6 A","24 A","0.25 A"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"I = V/R = 24/6 = 4 A, in parallel with the same 6 Ω resistance." },
{ q:"Two resistors, 6 Ω and 12 Ω, are connected in parallel. Find the equivalent resistance.",
  opts:["4 Ω","18 Ω","9 Ω","2 Ω"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"R_eq = (6×12)/(6+12) = 72/18 = 4 Ω." },
{ q:"For a symmetric delta network with each arm equal to R, the equivalent star network arm value is:",
  opts:["R/3","3R","R","R/√3"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"For a balanced delta-to-star transformation, each star arm equals one-third of the delta arm value." },
{ q:"A delta network has all three arms equal to 30 Ω. Find the equivalent star resistance per arm.",
  opts:["10 Ω","90 Ω","30 Ω","15 Ω"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"R_star = R_delta/3 = 30/3 = 10 Ω." },
{ q:"In a bridge network, the 'balance condition' is achieved when:",
  opts:["The products of opposite arm impedances are equal","All four arm impedances are numerically identical","The source voltage is zero","The bridge current is at its maximum value"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Balance occurs when the products of impedances in opposite arms match, driving the galvanometer/detector branch current to zero." },
{ q:"A 'passive' network element is one that:",
  opts:["Cannot supply net energy to the circuit over time, only absorbs or stores it","Always supplies energy continuously to the circuit","Requires an external power supply to function as a source","Only exists in AC circuits, never DC"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Resistors, inductors, and capacitors are passive — they dissipate or store energy but cannot deliver net energy over a complete cycle, unlike active sources." },
{ q:"A 'bilateral' circuit element is one whose:",
  opts:["V-I characteristic is the same regardless of the direction of current flow through it","Resistance changes when current direction reverses","Behaviour depends entirely on frequency","Voltage is always zero regardless of current"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"A resistor is a classic bilateral element — its behaviour doesn't change with current direction, unlike a diode, which is unilateral." },
{ q:"Nodal analysis is based on repeatedly applying which law at each independent node?",
  opts:["Kirchhoff's Current Law (KCL)","Kirchhoff's Voltage Law (KVL)","Ohm's Law only","Faraday's Law of induction"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Nodal analysis writes a KCL equation (sum of currents = 0) at each independent node to solve for node voltages." },
{ q:"Mesh analysis is based on repeatedly applying which law around each independent loop?",
  opts:["Kirchhoff's Voltage Law (KVL)","Kirchhoff's Current Law (KCL)","Ohm's Law only","Lenz's Law"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Mesh analysis writes a KVL equation (sum of voltage drops = 0) around each independent mesh/loop to solve for mesh currents." },
{ q:"The number of independent nodal equations required for a circuit with n total nodes (including the reference node) is:",
  opts:["n − 1","n","n + 1","2n"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"One node is chosen as the reference (0V), and KCL is applied at each of the remaining (n−1) nodes." },
{ q:"A circuit has 5 total nodes (including the reference node). How many independent nodal equations are required?",
  opts:["4","5","3","6"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Independent nodal equations = n − 1 = 5 − 1 = 4." },
{ q:"The number of independent mesh equations required for a circuit equals:",
  opts:["b − n + 1 (branches minus nodes plus 1)","b + n","n − 1","b − n"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"This formula gives the number of independent loops in a planar network, based on the total branches (b) and nodes (n)." },
{ q:"A circuit has 8 branches and 5 nodes. Find the number of independent mesh equations required.",
  opts:["4","3","5","8"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Independent mesh equations = b − n + 1 = 8 − 5 + 1 = 4." },
{ q:"A 'two-port network' is characterised by:",
  opts:["Two pairs of terminals (input and output ports), described using Z, Y, h, or ABCD parameters","A single pair of terminals only","Exactly two resistors connected in series","A network with no output terminals at all"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Two-port networks model devices/systems with distinct input and output ports, characterised using standard parameter sets like Z, Y, h, or ABCD." },
{ q:"In two-port Z-parameters, Z11 represents:",
  opts:["The input impedance with the output port open-circuited","The output impedance with the input port short-circuited","The overall gain of the network","The reverse transfer impedance"], ans:0, level:"Hard", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Z-parameters are defined under open-circuit conditions; Z11 is the input impedance measured with the output port left open." },
{ q:"In two-port h-parameters (hybrid parameters), h11 represents:",
  opts:["The input impedance with the output port short-circuited","The input admittance with the output port open-circuited","The forward current gain with the output open","The reverse voltage gain with the input shorted"], ans:0, level:"Hard", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Hybrid (h) parameters mix open- and short-circuit conditions; h11 specifically is the input impedance measured with the output port short-circuited." },
{ q:"ABCD (transmission) parameters of a two-port network are particularly useful for analysing:",
  opts:["Cascaded networks, since the overall ABCD matrix is the product of individual section matrices","Only single, isolated resistive networks","Circuits with no input source at all","Only purely capacitive networks"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"When two-port networks are connected in cascade (like transmission line sections), their combined ABCD matrix is simply the matrix product of each individual section." },
{ q:"A network is called 'reciprocal' if:",
  opts:["Interchanging the source and response doesn't change the ratio between them","It contains at least two independent sources","It has no passive elements at all","Its output is always greater than its input"], ans:0, level:"Medium", tag:"🟢 CONCEPT",
  exp:"Most passive, linear, bilateral networks are reciprocal, satisfying the condition described by the Reciprocity theorem." }
);

